** -um :: concretizing, nominalizing verbal suffix *** surely there is some use
   for this??? *** see /nunum/ thing *** _Examples of concretization_ ****
   /vîl/ yellow :: /vîlaz/ a yellow thing, smthg that is "yellowing" ****
   /hûdh/ to shit :: /hûdhax/ a turd, smthing that is shat **** /gakt/ to dance
   :: /jûk/ to enjoy :: /jûkâlen gaktâr/ :: I like to dance, I like dancing ***
   /wey/ to eat :: /weyum/ morsel, ort, a bit of food, a bait or serving of
   food, a plate (of food) *** /-um/ is used in /weyum/ because a morsel is a
   sort of fragment of something larger and neither /-ax, -az/, nor /-âr/ can
   express that :: the meaning of a /*portion*/ of something demands yet
   another concretizing suffix, but any new one suffices because of the
   /*lack*/ of activity in the object expressed with /-um/ 
**** /-az/ by definition is an entire thing engaged in an active verbal action
     and thus -az cannot express a morsel of food **** /-ax/ by definition is
     an entire thing that is being involved in a verbal activity by an agent,
     thus not a fragment or morsel, or at least it cannot denote such an
     object, for example, on a plate not yet in process of being eaten, thus
     the necessity of /-um/ 
 
** vîl ::  nominal :: yellow :: /vîlaz/ a yellow thing, smthg that is
"yellowing" *** vîlik :: adjective :: yellow 

